Can you use gdb or the visual studio debugger to figure out what
section of code it is crashing on and why (from a syntactic point of
view) is it crashing? It is important to know if it is because of a
NULL pointer, divide by zero, etc.. Also, it is crashing in the base
NEAT code or in your code?&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
If you are using unix/linux/mac, the code is already built with -pg, so
if you usually run your program like this:&lt;br&gt;
./Hypercube_&lt;wbr&gt;NEAT -I myinput.dat -O myoutput.xml&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
You can run it under gdb like this:&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
gdb --args ./Hypercube_&lt;wbr&gt;NEAT -I myinput.dat -O myoutput.xml&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
Then in the gdb prompt, type &quot;run&quot; and it will begin executing under
gdb. When it crashes, type &quot;bt&quot; to get a stack trace. This is critical
to figuring out why it is crashing.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
Under visual studio, run in debug mode (hit &#39;f5&#39;) and the same thing
should happen when something crashes.&lt;br&gt;
